“Yes, sir. They should already be on the road by now, and we gave them time to pack food from the mess hall.” 05:00 AM, Exodus assembled at the vehicle depot. Lieutenant Shaw stood on a box, beginning to speak.
“We will be fighting at the I-131 frontline base 50 miles outside Ianloss City. We will support the ongoing siege operation, then attack Ianloss City, and clear out the rebels there. We will use this as our base, and push into the mountains.” Lieutenant Shaw explained. “Take your team, and get ready to depart.”
The unit scattered, with each platoon mounting a tank under their respective platoon leader. Collins climbed onto the tank at the front of the convoy, sitting with Nimitz, Kress, and two new recruits. Collins remembered they had arrived just a few days ago, but didn't know them well. He sat on the edge of the tank, legs dangling, adjusting his backpack and radio equipment, and connecting it to his earpiece and throat microphone.
“Hey, Collins, does Harris still have Snowball?” Nimitz asked after they settled in.
“You mean the chicken he stole?” Collins remembered the scene from that morning when they stole chickens from the farm. “Yeah, I'm sure of it.”
Collins looked over at another tank and saw Harris and his teammates. He could faintly see a small chicken peeking out from behind Harris' backpack.
“Yeah, he still has that chicken,” Collins replied, and the tank's gun turret hatch opened with a clang, with the convoy leader appearing before them.
“All tanks are moving out,” the convoy leader said calmly into his earpiece. The tanks and Stryker armored vehicles of the armor platoon roared to life and began moving forward. Collins' Cronus tank released its brakes and moved forward, joining the convoy. The tanks formed a wedge formation as they crossed the Itanian plains, with the winter storm's snow and wind having frozen the wetlands and forests, but leaving mud still present.
About an hour later, one of the new recruits (Collins remembered his name was Osborn) asked, “Lieutenant, have you been on the front lines since the start of the war?”
“Yes, I have been since the Firestorm operation began,” Collins replied. “We thought it would be over in a few weeks, but… we underestimated them.”
“It's not just an underestimation.” Nimitz joined the conversation. “Their weapons and forces exceeded our expectations. They shot down UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Dammit, we should have seen it by now.”
“Well, I'll bravely fight for the federation.” Osen said resolutely. “I won't be intimidated by those terrorists.”
“You say that now, but from what I've seen, most new recruits your age would pee their pants at the sound of gunfire.” Kress said.
“Let's just see,” Collins said with a smile. Osen didn't say anything else.
“Exodus second-in-command! Exodus commander!” Collins' radio device called out. “We've detected a hot signal 20 degrees right front, 350 yards away.”
Colin climbed onto the tank, putting on his optical visor. Switching to heat imaging mode, he saw the distant heat signal.
“Yes, I see them.” Colin said into his throat microphone.
“Are they the enemy?” another new recruit, Natalie, asked.
“Can't tell.” Colin said, opening his microphone. “Exodus link, unless attacked, don't open fire, let's draw them out first.”
As they got closer, the faint heat signal transformed from a blurry spot into a clearer outline. One of them ran to somewhere, picked up something, and then ran back to the small hill. They then lay down, entering a firing position.
"We've encountered the enemy!" Lieutenant Commander Shaw shouted over the radio as orange tracers shot out from the ridge. The bullets hit the side of the tank with a clanging sound, and the team members jumped off the tank, taking cover behind it. A tank-fired missile screamed towards the rear of the tank column, exploding and sending shrapnel into one of the tanks. Another missile hit the side of an APS-Cerberus armored vehicle and exploded. After the explosion, the crew members inside the vehicle crawled out, looking for cover.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 yards. Open fire!" The tank commander shouted over the radio. The main guns of Iron 1-2 and 1-3 fired, and the shells whizzed towards the ridge, exploding and sending mud and rocks flying into the air.
"Send out scout robots!" Knox shouted, observing the ridge with his binoculars. A "hellhound" robot's rear door opened, and a soldier without a weapon stepped out, wearing a custom earpiece. He shouted orders into a square microphone, and two "scout" robots responded. Their thin metal arms and legs moved forward, and they quickly ran towards the ridge. The robots were equipped with weapons, but they were hung on their backs.
"Kill or capture?" Kress asked, observing and questioning.
"Looks like they're going to capture him," Colin speculated, watching as the two scout robots disappeared into the smoke and flames. The shouting and gunfire on the ridge subsided, and after a while, the two scout robots returned, dragging a person behind them. The prisoner's boots left a trail in the mud and snow as they were dragged. Once they reached the safe area, the robots threw the prisoner to the ground, and he landed heavily, groaning in pain.
He struggled to stand up, and Lieutenant Shaw came over. Shaw turned to one of the scouts. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," the scout robot replied. "The rest have fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Collins and Krebs, who were standing nearby, saying, "Can you two take this person away?"
